      "contentSections": [],
      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one keep their house if it's worth more than $2,000?",
          "answer": "Yes, your loved one's primary residence doesn't count toward the $2,000 asset limit regardless of value. Only cash, bank accounts, stocks, and other investments count as countable assets. The home remains exempt as long as your loved one lives in it."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one lives with me and I pay for their food?",
          "answer": "Free food and shelter count as in-kind income and will reduce your loved one's SSP payment. SSA calculates a dollar value for this support and deducts it from the monthly benefit amount. Keep records of any rent or food costs your loved one does pay."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for SSI and SSP on behalf of my elderly loved one?",
          "answer": "Yes, you can help your loved one apply or become their representative payee if SSA determines they can't manage their benefits. Call 1-800-772-1213 to discuss becoming an authorized representative during the application process."
        },
        {
          "question": "Why hasn't my loved one's SSP amount increased with cost of living?",
          "answer": "California's SSP supplement hasn't received annual cost-of-living adjustments since cuts made in 2009-2011. While federal SSI gets annual increases, the state portion remains fixed, meaning SSP benefits have lost purchasing power to inflation over time."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my loved one's income changes after they're approved?",
          "answer": "Report income changes to SSA immediately at 1-800-772-1213. SSP payments are reduced dollar-for-dollar by other countable income, so new income will decrease the monthly payment amount. SSA conducts periodic reviews to verify continued eligibility."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one receive SSP if they move to another state?",
          "answer": "No, SSP is only for California residents. If your loved one moves to another state, they'll lose the California supplement but may qualify for that state's supplemental payment if one exists. They must report address changes to SSA immediately."
        }
      ],
