      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "What happens to the postponed taxes when my loved one dies or we sell the house?",
          "answer": "The postponed taxes plus 7% annual interest become due immediately upon sale, transfer, death, or when your loved one stops living in the home as their primary residence. The state holds a lien on the property that must be paid from the sale proceeds or estate."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one apply if they co-own the house with someone under 62?",
          "answer": "All recorded property owners must be 62+, blind, or disabled, except for spouses, registered domestic partners, and direct-line relatives (children, grandchildren, or their spouses). If other co-owners don't meet these criteria, your loved one won't qualify."
        },
        {
          "question": "How much equity does my loved one need in their home to qualify?",
          "answer": "Your loved one must own at least 40% equity, meaning total mortgages, liens, and other encumbrances cannot exceed 60% of the property's fair market value. Any existing delinquent taxes count toward encumbrances and reduce available equity."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my loved one's income is slightly over $55,181?",
          "answer": "The income limit is firm at $55,181 for household income in the prior calendar year, regardless of household size. Income includes all household members except minors, full-time students, and renters. If income exceeds this limit, your loved one cannot qualify."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one postpone taxes if they already have a reverse mortgage?",
          "answer": "No, properties with reverse mortgages are not eligible for the Property Tax Postponement Program. This is a firm program requirement with no exceptions."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one misses the annual application deadline?",
          "answer": "Your loved one must wait until the next application period to apply. The program only accepts applications during specific months each year (typically October through February), and late applications are not accepted."
        }
      ],
